6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX uses oracle-based pricing with funding rates calculated against index price, sourced from Chainlink feeds and updated hourly. Bluefin employs traditional order book mechanics with funding rates derived from perpetual vs spot price differentials. GMX's oracle dependency can create basis risk during volatile periods, while Bluefin's order book model provides more granular price discovery. Both platforms update funding every hour, but GMX's rates tend to be more stable due to its pooled liquidity model versus Bluefin's market-driven approach."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which platform offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"GMX typically provides more stable funding rate patterns due to its oracle-based model, while Bluefin may offer higher volatility in rates but with lower trading fees. GMX's deeper liquidity makes it more suitable for larger arbitrage positions."},{"question":"How do the settlement mechanisms affect funding rate calculations?","answer":"GMX uses Chainlink oracles for price feeds, creating potential basis risk during volatile periods. Bluefin's order book model provides real-time price discovery but depends on sufficient market depth for accurate funding rate calculations."},{"question":"What are the key liquidity differences between these platforms?","answer":"GMX has significantly deeper liquidity through its GLP pools with over $100M TVL across supported chains. Bluefin, being newer on Sui, has limited liquidity which can create slippage issues for larger arbitrage trades."},{"question":"Which platform is more cost-effective for frequent funding rate trades?","answer":"Bluefin offers lower trading fees at 0.02%/0.05% compared to GMX's 0.05%/0.07%, making it more cost-effective for frequent arbitrage strategies. However, GMX's higher liquidity may offset fee differences for larger position sizes."}]}]
